      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What are the most common applications for a decanter centrifuge?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">The most common decanter centrifuge applications are wastewater sludge dewatering (municipal and industrial), food processing (olive oil extraction, rendering, starch processing), chemical processing (TiO2, CaCO3, kaolin), crude oil recovery and tank bottom sludge processing, waste oil reclamation, hemp extraction, and mining tailings dewatering. Decanter centrifuges are used wherever high volumes of slurry with 10–60% solids content need continuous separation into a dry cake and clarified liquid.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What is the difference between a decanter and a disc stack centrifuge for industrial applications?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">A decanter centrifuge handles high-solids slurries (10–60% solids) and produces a dry stackable cake using a horizontal bowl and scroll conveyor. A disc stack centrifuge handles low-solids fluids (under 5% solids) and achieves finer separation (down to 0.5 microns) at higher G-forces (up to 12,000 Gs vs. 3,000 Gs for decanters). Choose a decanter for high-volume sludge dewatering; choose a disc stack for fine clarification and liquid-liquid separation.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Can a decanter centrifuge handle oily sludge?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Yes. Decanter centrifuges are widely used for oily sludge applications including tank bottom sludge, refinery slop oil, marine oily bilge sludge, and crude oil production separators. For three-phase oil/water/solids separation, a 3-phase decanter (tricanter) is used, which has two liquid outlets in addition to the solids discharge. Heating the feed to 70–80°C significantly improves oil recovery from oily sludge.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What is the typical capacity range for decanter centrifuges?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Decanter centrifuge capacities range from 5 GPM (small pilot units) to over 2,000 GPM for large industrial models. Dolphin Centrifuge supplies Alfa Laval NX-314 (10–50 GPM), NX-418 (50–200 GPM), and G2-40 (100–400 GPM) decanter models. Capacity depends on feed solids content, required cake dryness, feed viscosity, and the separation factor — higher solids content reduces throughput for any given model.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
